always does that.

15:09.510 --> 15:10.611
I'll be right back.

15:30.931 --> 15:32.132
(NO SOUND)

15:34.968 --> 15:36.169
(NO SOUND)

15:46.179 --> 15:47.848
This is
what you should do.

15:47.881 --> 15:51.017
Find out her schedule
and memorize it.

15:51.051 --> 15:53.554
That way, you can bump
into her and say hi.

15:53.587 --> 15:56.757
Compliment her hair,
and the next time
you run into her,

15:56.790 --> 16:00.961
say, "Hey, did you
change your hair?"

16:00.994 --> 16:02.963
Pretty soon,
you'll have tons of
stuff to talk about.

16:02.996 --> 16:04.264
Good idea.

16:04.297 --> 16:07.734
And join all her
after‐school clubs.

16:07.768 --> 16:10.236
A, you'll get
to see her more.

16:10.270 --> 16:12.573
B, you'll get to
find out more
about her interests,

16:12.606 --> 16:14.074
and pretend they're
your interests, too.

16:14.107 --> 16:15.475
That makes sense.

16:15.876 --> 16:17.077
And C...

16:17.511 --> 16:19.279
Very important.

16:19.312 --> 16:22.348
You can make sure
she's not falling in
love with anyone else,

16:23.016 --> 16:24.484
Like your friend Bill.

16:24.518 --> 16:27.153
You think Cindy'll
fall in love with bill?

16:27.187 --> 16:29.523
I don't know.
Being lab partners

16:29.556 --> 16:32.025
is like getting stranded
on a desert island.

16:32.058 --> 16:33.660
You never know
what might happen.

16:35.328 --> 16:38.031
Hey, man, I heard
Kim got an "A" on her
world civ test.

16:38.064 --> 16:39.766
That's great.
Huh?

16:40.801 --> 16:42.736
Oh, no, that's right.

16:42.769 --> 16:44.938
That was my girlfriend.

16:44.971 --> 16:47.207
Oh, that's
really funny.

16:48.775 --> 16:50.777
Ah, you know what,
though?

16:50.811 --> 16:53.413
Oh, man.
Lindsay got detention.

16:53.446 --> 16:55.649
For flipping off
her gym teacher.

16:57.150 --> 16:59.052
Oh, no,
that's right.

16:59.085 --> 17:02.623
That was
your girlfriend. Ohh!

17:04.090 --> 17:06.593
I heard Kim punched
you in the chest
really hard.

17:07.661 --> 17:09.029
Oh, whoops.
That was me!

17:09.062 --> 17:10.263
Ohh! Aah!

17:13.066 --> 17:14.601
That was really hard.

17:16.436 --> 17:18.471
I'm telling you,
she's abnormal.

17:18.505 --> 17:21.041
She eats
carrot sticks, and
she likes Miss Piggy.

17:21.074 --> 17:23.810
So what?
The Muppets are cool.

17:23.844 --> 17:26.012
Yeah, Swedish chef
is kinda cool,

17:26.046 --> 17:27.213
but Miss Piggy's lame.

17:27.247 --> 17:29.683
Look, Professor Honeywell
was hysterical.

17:29.716 --> 17:31.585
Cindy is
not abnormal.

17:32.819 --> 17:34.220
Yeah?

17:34.254 --> 17:35.656
She cut the cheese.

17:35.689 --> 17:36.823
Ooh, my God!

17:36.857 --> 17:38.391
That's not funny.

17:39.593 --> 17:40.861
I heard it, man.
I swear.

17:40.894 --> 17:42.996
She blamed it
on the chair,

17:43.029 --> 17:45.231
but she cut the cheese.

17:45.265 --> 17:48.935
Well, some chairs
make weird noises!

17:48.969 --> 17:50.470
What kind of
a chair was it?

17:50.504 --> 17:51.538
I don't know.

17:52.038 --> 17:53.507
Vinyl?

17:53.540 --> 17:55.642
Well, vinyl chairs
always squeak.

17:55.676 --> 17:56.943
It wasn't a squeak.

17:56.977 --> 17:58.612
It was the sound
of cheese being cut.

17:58.645 --> 17:59.780
(GIGGLES)

17:59.813 --> 18:02.983
You know what?
I think you're
making all of this up.

18:03.016 --> 18:06.019
because you want me
to stop liking her,

18:06.052 --> 18:07.588
because you like her now.

18:07.621 --> 18:08.622
What?

18:09.756 --> 18:10.757
CINDY: Bill?

18:12.192 --> 18:13.560
Hey, guys, what's up?

18:13.594 --> 18:15.295
Oh, hi, Cindy.

18:15.328 --> 18:16.963
You changed your hair.

18:16.997 --> 18:20.033
It just looks
really flat today.

18:20.066 --> 18:22.235
Oh, Bill,
I wanted to tell you.

18:22.268 --> 18:23.737
I have a yearbook
meeting after school,

18:23.770 --> 18:25.872
but we can work
on our lab assignment
afterwards.

18:25.906 --> 18:27.473
Oh, I can't wait.

18:27.508 --> 18:30.443
Maybe this time,
you can come over
to my house.

18:30.476 --> 18:31.678
CINDY: OK.

18:31.712 --> 18:32.713
Oh, and by the way,

18:32.746 --> 18:35.215
I finally got to see
<i>Welcome Back, Kotter.</i>

18:35.248 --> 18:39.319
You were right.
Mr. Woodman is so funny.

18:39.352 --> 18:40.987
Yeah, I'm tellin' ya,

18:41.021 --> 18:43.023
that guy is
totally underrated.

18:43.056 --> 18:44.257
(LAUGHS)

18:47.728 --> 18:48.729
Um...

18:51.031 --> 18:53.567
Lindsay, it's a test,
not a race.

18:53.600 --> 18:56.236
And if it were a race,
Millie already beat you.

19:11.685 --> 19:12.853
(WHISPERING) Millie?

19:14.454 --> 19:15.556
Millie?

19:16.322 --> 19:17.891
I need to talk to you.

19:18.825 --> 19:19.960
Why?

19:19.993 --> 19:21.227
I just do.

19:23.564 --> 19:24.565
Yes?

19:26.667 --> 19:29.636
Remember when we used
to love Leif Garrett?

19:29.670 --> 19:31.905
And we used to take my
Dynamite magazines out

19:31.938 --> 19:33.273
and kiss his picture?

19:33.874 --> 19:35.208
Yeah.

19:35.241 --> 19:37.277
And we went to see him
at the state fair

19:37.310 --> 19:39.580
and cut all the way
to the front row.

19:39.613 --> 19:42.749
It turned out to be
Jack Albertson from
<i>Chico and the Man.</i>

19:43.183 --> 19:44.551
Oh, yeah.

19:45.251 --> 19:47.120
That kinda sucked.

19:47.153 --> 19:48.755
It wasn't so bad.

19:49.289 --> 19:50.657
It was kinda funny.

19:52.492 --> 19:54.160
Millie, I'm just
saying that

19:54.194 --> 19:56.162
we always dreamed
of having a boyfriend,

19:56.196 --> 19:58.965
and I think I finally
have a boyfriend,

19:58.999 --> 20:00.901
and I think
he wants to have sex.

20:03.169 --> 20:05.506
You can't have sex
with Nick.

20:05.539 --> 20:07.774
Once you do, you'll
never be the same again.

20:09.109 --> 20:11.545
Plus no one would
want to marry you.

20:12.278 --> 20:13.479
Why should they
buy the cow

20:13.514 --> 20:15.415
when they can get
the milk for free?

20:18.652 --> 20:20.286
Some of you will be
happy to see that,

20:20.320 --> 20:21.788
after several
complaints,

20:21.822 --> 20:24.725
I have eliminated
"disco days"
from the running.

20:24.758 --> 20:25.892
Thank you very much.

20:25.926 --> 20:27.828
TEACHER:
Who's got photographs?
Hey, Cindy.

20:27.861 --> 20:28.695
TEACHER: OK.
Hey, Sam.

20:28.729 --> 20:30.764
I didn't know you
were on yearbook.

20:30.797 --> 20:32.232
Did you just join?

20:32.265 --> 20:34.200
Uh... Yeah.

20:34.234 --> 20:36.336
I want to become
more involved in

20:36.369 --> 20:38.271
After‐school activities.

20:38.304 --> 20:39.740
That's cool.

20:39.773 --> 20:40.974
Any article ideas?

20:42.509 --> 20:43.476
Cindy?

20:43.510 --> 20:45.912
Uh, it's called
"Diary of
a McKinley student."

20:45.946 --> 20:49.015
It describes
a high school student's
experience.

20:49.049 --> 20:50.316
Go ahead. Read it.

20:52.919 --> 20:55.155
"September 3, 1980.

20:55.188 --> 20:56.823
"Freshman year.

20:56.857 --> 20:57.958
"Dear diary,

20:57.991 --> 21:00.160
"High school.
So cavernous.

21:00.193 --> 21:01.595
"Cold, uninviting.

21:01.628 --> 21:04.364
"Starting over.
No identity.

21:04.397 --> 21:06.867
"Everyone looking,
everyone judging.

21:06.900 --> 21:07.934
(SNICKERS)

21:07.968 --> 21:09.302
"Their eyes
pierce my soul.

21:09.335 --> 21:11.371
"Aimless youth,
all trapped together,

21:11.404 --> 21:13.139
"but no one connecting.

21:13.173 --> 21:15.408
"Education or isolation?

21:15.942 --> 21:16.977
"Class dismissed."

21:20.647 --> 21:22.048
MAINZER: OK.

21:22.082 --> 21:24.150
Thank you,
Sylvia Plath.

21:24.184 --> 21:28.922
Uh...
It's a little dark.

21:28.955 --> 21:31.825
We want
to sell yearbooks,
not tell the truth.

21:32.492 --> 21:33.493
OK.

21:34.194 --> 21:35.696
It was just an idea.

21:35.729 --> 21:36.930
OK.

21:36.963 --> 21:39.833
The next thing we need
to talk about is ad sales.

21:39.866 --> 21:40.934
(STUDENTS GROAN)

21:40.967 --> 21:43.203
Yes, I know. It's no fun.

21:43.236 --> 21:44.638
It's not creative,

21:44.671 --> 21:47.207
but if we don't
sell the rest of this
ad space by tomorrow,

21:47.240 --> 21:48.875
we won't have enough
money for printing.

21:48.909 --> 21:51.545
Here's a list
of the local merchants
we haven't hit yet.

21:51.578 --> 21:55.582
Um... My dad owns
A‐1 Sporting Goods.

21:55.616 --> 21:56.449
Great!

21:56.482 --> 21:58.084
You can start
with his store.

21:58.118 --> 21:59.886
why don't you
pair up with Cindy?

22:00.120 --> 22:01.287
Sure.

22:01.321 --> 22:03.657
Mr. Stoker,
you pair up with Carl.

22:03.690 --> 22:06.326
Can you believe we have
to sell yearbook ads?

22:06.359 --> 22:09.029
Yeah. That really sucks.

22:17.470 --> 22:18.972
MRS. WEIR: Hey, Lindsay.

22:19.005 --> 22:20.974
I got something
to show you.

22:23.076 --> 22:24.077
What?

22:25.011 --> 22:26.179
What's up?

22:26.212 --> 22:28.381
Somebody likes you,
that's what's up.

22:29.449 --> 22:31.652
I didn't know
you had a boyfriend.

22:31.685 --> 22:32.786
What's his name?
What's he like?

22:32.819 --> 22:34.487
I want to know
everything, really.

22:34.521 --> 22:37.157
(LAUGHS)
He's just a friend.

22:37.190 --> 22:39.425
A friend?
Do I know him?

22:40.293 --> 22:41.962
Well, open the card.

22:41.995 --> 22:43.530
Mama!
What? What?

22:44.264 --> 22:45.465
Sweetie?

22:58.078 --> 23:00.413
"W‐A‐T‐E."

23:02.849 --> 23:04.084
(LAUGHS)

23:13.527 --> 23:15.529
My dad's store
is right down
the block.

23:15.562 --> 23:17.531
Yeah?
All right, great.

23:18.064 --> 23:19.165
(SIGHS)

23:20.701 --> 23:23.336
You know, I really
liked what you wrote
for the yearbook.

23:23.369 --> 23:24.771
It was really cool.

23:24.805 --> 23:27.440
I think Mr. Mainzer
doesn't know what
he's talking about.

23:28.308 --> 23:29.576
Thanks.

23:30.844 --> 23:32.412
And you know,
you're right.

23:32.445 --> 23:34.047
Being a freshman stinks.

23:34.648 --> 23:36.282
I know, it's like...

23:36.316 --> 23:38.451
Everyone pigeonholes
you and expects you

23:38.484 --> 23:40.386
to act a certain way.

23:40.420 --> 23:41.888
It's like if
you're a cheerleader,

23:41.922 --> 23:44.157
you're supposed to be
in a good mood all the time.

23:44.190 --> 23:45.626
Yeah, that
must be tough.

23:45.659 --> 23:47.293
I know! It's like
there are some days

23:47.327 --> 23:49.563
when I'm just feeling
a little bit cranky.

23:49.963 --> 23:50.964
Like today.

23:50.997 --> 23:53.934
I just got my period.
So what? Deal with it.

23:56.970 --> 23:58.171
All right,
thanks, Mike.

23:58.204 --> 24:00.140
And good luck
with that bomb shelter.

24:00.173 --> 24:01.508
(BELL ON DOOR RINGS)

24:02.375 --> 24:03.644
MR. WEIR: Sam?

24:03.677 --> 24:05.679
I thought you were going
to help me out today.

24:05.712 --> 24:07.948
Oh, yeah, I was
at a yearbook meeting.

24:07.981 --> 24:09.516
(BELL RINGS)

24:09.550 --> 24:11.051
yearbook? when the heck
did you join that?

24:11.084 --> 24:12.118
Uh, today.

24:12.152 --> 24:13.587
This is
my friend Cindy.

24:13.620 --> 24:15.155
Hi. Nice to meet you.

24:15.188 --> 24:18.424
Hello.
Uh, look, Sam.

24:18.458 --> 24:20.561
Now, look, you gotta
put in your time.

24:20.594 --> 24:22.228
I'm trying to teach
you a work ethic here.

24:22.262 --> 24:25.265
Now, if you want
to buy those crazy
micronaut things,

24:25.298 --> 24:27.267
you're going to have
to earn the money.

24:27.300 --> 24:29.002
Oh, for cryin' out loud,

24:29.035 --> 24:31.471
who mixed up the balls?

24:31.505 --> 24:34.941
Um, you have
a really nice store,
Mr. Weir.

24:34.975 --> 24:37.611
Dave, bring up
those boxes up there.

24:38.278 --> 24:41.281
Uh, Dad, Cindy and I...

24:41.314 --> 24:43.850
Well, we're
selling yearbook ads.

24:43.884 --> 24:48.855
And 1/8 of a page is $25.
Do you want to buy one?

24:48.889 --> 24:50.423
1/8 for $25?

24:50.456 --> 24:51.725
Sam, that's
highway robbery!

24:51.758 --> 24:54.260
I can get a full
page in a Sunday
paper for a hundred.

24:54.294 --> 24:55.896
But this is
really important

24:55.929 --> 24:58.331
that Cindy and I
sell these.

24:58.364 --> 24:59.700
(BELL ON DOOR CHIMES)

25:01.868 --> 25:04.505
Oh, well,
tell you what.

25:04.538 --> 25:06.072
Give me a full page.

25:07.273 --> 25:08.842
Wow! thank you,
Mr. Weir.

25:08.875 --> 25:11.512
No problem.
Sam is my best
salesman, you know?

25:11.545 --> 25:12.746
Really?

25:13.814 --> 25:16.016
OK, so we've got
16 more ads to sell,

25:16.049 --> 25:17.784
and I think we should go
to the big stores first

25:17.818 --> 25:19.085
since they'll probably
buy more space.

25:19.119 --> 25:21.421
Yeah, but
the small stores
close earlier, so...

25:21.454 --> 25:24.525
Oh, wait a minute now.
you're squandering
your manpower.

25:24.558 --> 25:25.926
What you gotta do
is split up,

25:25.959 --> 25:27.894
and, you know,
take separate routes.

25:27.928 --> 25:29.763
That way you can
cover more ground.

25:30.531 --> 25:31.865
CINDY: Thank you.

25:33.534 --> 25:35.501
But then again,

25:35.536 --> 25:38.471
some of the greatest
salesmen worked in teams.

25:38.505 --> 25:40.741
Yeah, maybe we should
stick together.

25:40.774 --> 25:42.609
Yeah, but we'll both
finish sooner if we split up,

25:42.643 --> 25:43.877
Don't you think?

25:47.113 --> 25:48.582
Yeah, I guess so.

25:49.382 --> 25:51.017
Thank you, Mr. Weir.

25:52.418 --> 25:53.720
See ya, Dad.

25:57.457 --> 25:58.959
Sir, don't open that bait.

26:00.260 --> 26:03.496
So I saw Sam's
yearbook partner
at the store today.

26:03.530 --> 26:05.131
Quite a cute
little number.

26:05.165 --> 26:07.367
Hmm.
God, Dad!

26:07.400 --> 26:09.636
What? What's
wrong with that?

26:09.670 --> 26:10.937
She's cute.

26:10.971 --> 26:12.806
Am I supposed
to call her "Ms."
or something?

26:12.839 --> 26:16.442
See, Lindsay,
Sam's not afraid to
show off his girlfriend.

26:16.476 --> 26:17.678
Mom!

26:20.380 --> 26:22.348
What's eating you?
Ah, just...

26:23.617 --> 26:25.118
Lindsay has a boyfriend.

26:25.552 --> 26:26.587
Oh, my God!

26:26.620 --> 26:27.988
What? Who?

26:28.021 --> 26:29.723
(LAUGHS)

26:29.756 --> 26:32.526
Someone sent her
a red rose.

26:32.559 --> 26:34.728
He must be
some kind of Romeo.

26:34.761 --> 26:35.962
Yeah, I'll say he is.

26:35.996 --> 26:37.531
Who the hell
is this joker?

26:37.564 --> 26:39.232
He's just a friend.

26:39.265 --> 26:42.468
Nobody who's
"just a friend"
sends a single rose.

26:42.503 --> 26:44.605
I know all about
single roses.

26:44.638 --> 26:45.706
I sent one
to your mother,

26:45.739 --> 26:47.574
and I know when
and why I sent it.

26:47.608 --> 26:48.909
MRS. WEIR: Harold.

26:48.942 --> 26:51.177
Lindsay, you can
tell us who it is,

26:51.211 --> 26:54.080
and we won't make
a big deal out of it,
all right?

26:54.515 --> 26:55.749
LINDSAY: OK.

26:56.316 --> 26:57.618
OK, it's Nick.

26:58.118 --> 26:59.520
Nick?
Nick?

26:59.553 --> 27:01.788
It's not another one
of those burn‐outs.

27:01.822 --> 27:02.956
No!

27:02.989 --> 27:06.059
Nick? Was he the one that
ate all my fruit roll‐ups?

27:06.092 --> 27:07.661
Well, you said
he could have them.

27:07.694 --> 27:09.630
No, I... I know. I...

27:09.663 --> 27:11.264
Well, you'd better
know right now

27:11.297 --> 27:13.534
that your mother
and I are not
taking care of

27:13.567 --> 27:15.035
some "wedlock" baby,

27:15.068 --> 27:16.970
while you're off
gallivanting at college.

27:17.203 --> 27:18.238
Dad!

27:18.271 --> 27:19.305
I'm warning you, Lindsay.

27:19.339 --> 27:22.308
I absolutely forbid you
from seeing this boy.

27:32.719 --> 27:34.287
Well, at least
she didn't yell.

27:35.455 --> 27:36.690
Honey.

27:44.497 --> 27:47.100
See, you don't know
what it's like

27:47.133 --> 27:49.603
to have a daughter
and want to protect her.

27:49.636 --> 27:52.105
Well, I mean,
you will someday.

27:52.138 --> 27:55.175
We'd like that day
to be a long time
from now.

27:55.208 --> 27:59.079
We just want to be sure
that this boy respects
you, honey.

27:59.112 --> 28:00.413
Not all of them do.

28:00.446 --> 28:02.248
Trust me. I know
what they're like.

28:02.282 --> 28:03.483
I was one of them.

28:03.517 --> 28:05.218
Ugh! he was.

28:06.019 --> 28:08.421
I know. You find it
hard to believe,

28:08.454 --> 28:11.592
but I did
some stupid things
when I was young.

28:11.625 --> 28:12.826
Honey.

28:14.360 --> 28:16.029
Tell her about Korea.

28:17.063 --> 28:18.198
Ko...

28:19.265 --> 28:20.333
Rea.

28:22.335 --> 28:24.838
Well, one day...

28:25.939 --> 28:29.309
I, uh, went into Seoul
on a weekend pass

28:30.243 --> 28:32.746
and went to this bar.

28:33.780 --> 28:36.349
And I had
a few too many.

28:36.382 --> 28:37.383
And...

28:38.785 --> 28:42.122
I followed a couple
of my buddies to the...

28:43.724 --> 28:44.958
Red‐light district.

28:44.991 --> 28:47.460
Your father's first time
wasn't special,

28:48.428 --> 28:50.697
and he's always
regretted it.

28:50.731 --> 28:53.299
It was the worst
$5.00 I've ever spent.

28:55.068 --> 28:58.839
And I wish I could get
that $5.00 back.

28:58.872 --> 29:01.908
Ohh, come on! please stop!

29:01.942 --> 29:05.011
W... What your father
is trying to say is...

29:06.012 --> 29:08.314
That your virginity is...

29:08.348 --> 29:09.750
A gift.

29:43.817 --> 29:44.951
Let's get out of here.

29:44.985 --> 29:46.853
Hold on a second.
I gotta find my smokes.

29:46.887 --> 29:48.188
Did you take 'em?

29:48.221 --> 29:49.255
No.

29:49.289 --> 29:50.824
Hey, man, we're goin'
to Des's tonight.

29:50.857 --> 29:52.092
Are you coming?

29:52.125 --> 29:53.059
No. Oh, hey.

29:53.093 --> 29:55.596
No, actually, I'm
hangin' out with Linds.

29:55.629 --> 29:58.064
Ohh, all right.
Make it happen.

29:58.098 --> 30:01.735
Oh, tonight's
the niiight!

30:01.768 --> 30:03.904
Ooh!
Call me tomorrow, Lindsay.

30:03.937 --> 30:05.338
I want to know
everything that happens.

30:05.371 --> 30:07.340
So do I, Lindsay.

30:07.373 --> 30:10.711
Keep yawnin' like that,
you're gonna dislocate
your jaw.

30:10.744 --> 30:12.979
Guys, wait up.

30:13.013 --> 30:15.582
Hey, Sam.
you know what Cindy
said last night?

30:16.583 --> 30:18.251
What? that she's
in love with you?

30:18.284 --> 30:21.855
That... That she thinks
you're smart and funny

30:21.888 --> 30:24.558
and you don't care
if she cuts the cheese?

30:24.591 --> 30:26.259
You know what, Bill?

30:26.292 --> 30:27.961
Why don't you
just go out with her?

30:27.994 --> 30:30.330
Why don't you
marry her? I don't
care anymore, OK?

30:30.363 --> 30:31.364
I don't care.

30:32.132 --> 30:33.166
God!

30:33.199 --> 30:34.868
I was gonna say

30:34.901 --> 30:36.770
she said
she thought

30:36.803 --> 30:38.404
you were the nicest guy
in the school.

30:39.873 --> 30:41.207
Cindy said that?

30:41.675 --> 30:42.876
Yeah.

30:43.510 --> 30:45.145
No, wait. No, seriously.

30:46.379 --> 30:47.548
You don't like Cindy?

30:48.381 --> 30:50.316
No. Man, I was just
messin' with you.

30:50.350 --> 30:53.053
Sam, Bill's been in love
with Melissa Karpinski

30:53.086 --> 30:55.722
ever since he stood behind
her at the Dairy Queen.

30:55.756 --> 30:57.791
She was wearing
this halter top.

30:57.824 --> 30:58.859
(GROANS)

30:58.892 --> 31:01.895
She is
one foxy lady.

31:01.928 --> 31:03.363
She doesn't
cut the cheese.

31:03.396 --> 31:04.264
(BOTH LAUGH)

31:04.297 --> 31:06.132
Come on! Everybody
cuts the cheese.

31:06.166 --> 31:08.569
Anyways
Melissa Karpinski is
way out of your league.

31:08.602 --> 31:11.137
She goes out with,
like, the big
football players.

31:11.171 --> 31:12.038
Ooh.

31:12.072 --> 31:13.574
(SCHOOL BELL RINGS)

31:14.641 --> 31:15.876
I'm going
to fill out soon.

31:15.909 --> 31:17.177
You know
my cousin Jeff?

31:17.210 --> 31:18.912
He was a shrimp
until he turned 16,

31:18.945 --> 31:20.446
and then he got all
tall and muscular,

31:20.480 --> 31:21.548
like, in a month.

31:21.582 --> 31:23.083
Now he looks
like the Hulk.

31:24.250 --> 31:25.952
You really think
I'll fill out?

31:25.986 --> 31:28.221
Yeah, not like me,
though.

31:28.254 --> 31:29.956
In 3 years, I'm going
to be enormous.

31:29.990 --> 31:32.893
Oh, yeah. Me, too.
My dad is 6'3".

31:32.926 --> 31:35.261
Hey, listen, you guys.

31:35.295 --> 31:38.532
Why don't we go see
Airplane again on Saturday?

31:38.932 --> 31:40.133
Surely you will.

31:40.500 --> 31:41.668
OK.

31:41.702 --> 31:43.504
Don't call me Shirley.

31:43.537 --> 31:45.071
(LAUGHS)

31:45.105 --> 31:48.174
Billy,
have you ever seen
a grown man naked?

31:49.610 --> 31:53.046
Hey, why don't we go
ask Gordon to come
with us?

31:53.614 --> 31:54.615
But...

31:55.215 --> 31:56.149
He smells.

31:56.182 --> 31:58.384
Yeah, yeah, yeah, I know.

31:58.418 --> 32:00.420
But he's really cool.

32:01.221 --> 32:03.423
Maybe he doesn't
even know he smells.

32:04.991 --> 32:06.527
Are you gonna tell him?

32:10.731 --> 32:11.932
Hey, Gordon.

32:11.965 --> 32:14.500
Hey. Uh, how's it going
with you‐know‐who?

32:14.535 --> 32:16.302
Did you join her clubs?

32:16.336 --> 32:17.904
Yeah, yeah.

32:17.938 --> 32:19.506
And we got
to hang out.

32:20.707 --> 32:22.408
Uh, sort of.
Cool.

32:23.644 --> 32:25.779
You know,
she smells great.

32:25.812 --> 32:27.681
It must be her shampoo.

32:27.714 --> 32:30.717
Or... Deodorant
or something.

32:30.751 --> 32:33.286
What kind of deodorant
do you use?

32:34.621 --> 32:37.057
I know I smell, Sam.

32:37.090 --> 32:39.159
W... W... What are you
talking about?

32:39.192 --> 32:41.962
I may be smelly,
but I'm not stupid.

32:43.329 --> 32:45.832
OK. So...

32:45.866 --> 32:47.000
What is that?

32:47.033 --> 32:48.835
It's a medical condition.

32:48.869 --> 32:50.604
It's called
tryptophanuria.

32:50.637 --> 32:51.638
It's genetic.

32:53.607 --> 32:55.341
Wow! Is there a cure?

32:55.375 --> 32:58.411
Not yet, but research
is progressing.

33:02.048 --> 33:04.851
So you're
going to be...

33:04.885 --> 33:06.620
Smelly the rest
of your life?

33:06.653 --> 33:08.989
Mm‐hmm.
But I don't mind.

33:09.022 --> 33:10.256
Nice people
don't care,

33:10.290 --> 33:12.092
and it weeds out
the jerks.

33:12.125 --> 33:13.727
My mom says
it's a gift.

33:15.261 --> 33:16.296
Cool.

33:16.963 --> 33:18.932
You know...

33:18.965 --> 33:23.069
Uh, Neal, Bill, and I
are going to the movies
Saturday night.

33:23.103 --> 33:24.470
You want to come with us?

33:24.905 --> 33:26.239
OK.

33:26.272 --> 33:27.941
I'll try not to
stink up the joint.

33:27.974 --> 33:29.342
(SAM LAUGHS)

33:29.375 --> 33:30.410
Just kidding.

33:30.443 --> 33:31.778
Yeah, I know.

33:32.378 --> 33:34.347
CINDY: Hey, Sam.

33:34.380 --> 33:36.517
So how'd it go?
did you sell
all your ads?

33:36.917 --> 33:38.418
No, not really.

33:38.451 --> 33:41.321
That's OK. No one
else did except for me.

33:41.354 --> 33:43.990
So I'm really glad that
you joined yearbook.

33:44.024 --> 33:45.926
I had a lot of fun
yesterday.

33:45.959 --> 33:47.393
Yeah, me, too.

33:49.029 --> 33:51.064
So anyway, what are you
doing after school?

33:52.032 --> 33:54.000
Well, is there
another yearbook meeting?

33:54.034 --> 33:55.902
Well, no, I was just
going to go to Sackie's,

33:55.936 --> 33:58.138
and I was wondering
if you wanted to come.

33:58.171 --> 34:00.173
Don't touch the hair!

34:00.774 --> 34:01.775
Stop it!

34:03.677 --> 34:06.547
Yeah, yeah, I'll come.

34:06.580 --> 34:08.481
Definitely. Sure.

34:08.515 --> 34:09.550
Great.

34:09.583 --> 34:10.416
(BELL RINGS)

34:10.450 --> 34:12.252
Tardy. I better
go sit down.

34:13.720 --> 34:15.321
See you after school.

34:15.355 --> 34:16.356
See ya.

34:16.389 --> 34:18.224
(IMITATES CINDY)
See you after school.

34:22.095 --> 34:23.463
Thanks, Sam.

34:25.365 --> 34:27.267
Look, are you sure
you don't need any money?

34:28.068 --> 34:29.469
Y... Yeah, I'm fine.

34:33.840 --> 34:36.242
Mmm, I love
bacon cheeseburgers.

34:36.910 --> 34:38.378
Really?

34:38.411 --> 34:41.982
I kinda expected you
to like, you know,

34:42.015 --> 34:45.185
healthy food
like carrots.

34:45.451 --> 34:46.520
E‐yuck!

34:46.553 --> 34:49.189
If I never saw another carrot
again, it'd be too soon.

34:49.222 --> 34:51.558
I mean, my parents
never take us to Sackie's.

34:51.592 --> 34:54.294
That's why I have
to sneak here after school.

34:58.632 --> 35:00.834
Uh... Want some?

35:00.867 --> 35:02.135
Sure, thanks.

35:02.168 --> 35:05.305
(INAUDIBLE CONVERSATION)

35:06.372 --> 35:07.941
He's smiling and nodding
because he wants me

35:07.974 --> 35:09.175
to pass him the ball.

35:09.209 --> 35:10.744
So I throw it to him,

35:10.777 --> 35:11.812
and he ducks
like a girl.

35:11.845 --> 35:13.246
(LAUGHTER)

35:17.050 --> 35:18.719
Do you know
Todd Schellinger?

35:21.087 --> 35:22.288
Yeah.

35:23.089 --> 35:25.626
Well, not personally.

35:26.627 --> 35:27.628
But...

35:28.829 --> 35:29.896
Why?

35:34.100 --> 35:36.002
I... I don't know.

35:36.036 --> 35:37.771
He's kinda cute,
don't you think?

35:39.039 --> 35:40.507
(UNEASY LAUGH)

35:40.541 --> 35:42.242
I... I guess.

35:42.275 --> 35:45.679
OK, I've never really
told anyone this before.

35:45.712 --> 35:49.850
But I have, like,
the hugest crush on him.

35:51.785 --> 35:53.053
At last week's game,

35:53.086 --> 35:54.921
he asked my friend Joe
for my phone number.

35:56.523 --> 35:58.291
Do you think that means
he likes me?

35:59.459 --> 36:01.562
He... He asked for
your phone number?

36:02.629 --> 36:04.264
Well, yeah, but...

36:04.297 --> 36:05.832
I mean, he never called.

36:05.866 --> 36:09.302
And every time I see him,
he acts like he doesn't
even know I exist.

36:11.371 --> 36:13.640
Well, maybe
he's just shy.

36:13.674 --> 36:14.675
You think?

36:18.178 --> 36:20.013
I don't know.

36:20.046 --> 36:22.115
It's, like, I'm always
so nervous around him.

36:22.148 --> 36:23.650
I never know
what to say.

36:26.219 --> 36:27.654
It's not like with you.

36:30.156 --> 36:32.526
You're so easy
to talk to.

36:32.559 --> 36:34.661
You're just
like my sister.

36:37.964 --> 36:38.965
Thanks.

36:40.333 --> 36:42.402
Oh, my God,
did he just look at me?

36:42.836 --> 36:43.837
Don't look.

36:47.140 --> 36:48.509
MAN ON TV:
Go, go, go, go, go!

36:48.542 --> 36:50.410
(TIRES SCREECHING)
MAN: Ohh!

36:51.144 --> 36:53.046
Have a nice time, honey.

36:53.079 --> 36:54.214
Don't stay out
too late.

36:54.247 --> 36:56.517
I won't. Bye.

36:56.717 --> 36:57.818
Bye.

36:58.785 --> 37:00.587
MAN ON TV: We need backup.

37:03.023 --> 37:04.257
Sam?

37:04.958 --> 37:06.259
Hey, son.

37:07.961 --> 37:09.229
Yeah?

37:09.262 --> 37:11.665
Come on over here and
join your mom and dad, huh?

37:12.899 --> 37:14.200
Why? What did I do?

37:14.234 --> 37:16.302
(LAUGHS)
Nothing, silly.

37:16.336 --> 37:19.039
Come on.
Get your butt over here.

37:19.072 --> 37:20.774
MRS. WEIR:
"What did I do?"

37:20.807 --> 37:21.908
MR. WEIR: Come on.

37:22.676 --> 37:23.910
(LAUGHS)

37:23.944 --> 37:25.646
(POLICE SIRENS ON TV)

37:29.482 --> 37:30.483
Um...

37:31.084 --> 37:32.519
I have homework.

37:33.286 --> 37:35.221
You can do it tomorrow.

37:35.255 --> 37:36.723
Family time's
more important.

37:36.757 --> 37:38.358
(TIRES SCREECHING)

37:44.831 --> 37:46.466
(CAR CRASHES)

37:56.309 --> 37:57.410
(DOORBELL RINGS)

37:57.443 --> 37:59.045
(RUNNING FOOTSTEPS)

37:59.079 --> 38:00.781
Oh, hi!

38:00.814 --> 38:02.816
Y... You must have been
right there.

38:03.817 --> 38:04.885
Perfect timing.

38:05.686 --> 38:06.787
Come on in.

38:10.423 --> 38:12.593
I hope you like
The Moody Blues.

38:12.626 --> 38:14.595
Oh, yeah,
they're really great.

38:14.628 --> 38:16.196
I know,
they're kind of wimpy,

38:16.229 --> 38:17.931
but I think
this song's OK.

38:17.964 --> 38:18.965
Yeah.

38:21.702 --> 38:22.703
So...

38:24.004 --> 38:26.439
Wow! Whose
basketball trophies?

38:26.472 --> 38:29.075
Yeah, they're mine.
I actually used to play.

38:29.109 --> 38:30.243
Ohh.

38:30.276 --> 38:32.579
Well, why'd you quit?

38:32.613 --> 38:34.548
They found a dime bag
in my locker,

38:34.581 --> 38:36.517
and then they kicked me
off the team.

38:36.550 --> 38:38.519
And then I just
lost interest.

38:43.023 --> 38:45.826
Oh, yeah. No, that one's
actually for bowling.

38:51.632 --> 38:54.034
Do you want to hang out
downstairs for a while?

38:54.067 --> 38:55.769
Whoa! Uh...

38:56.703 --> 38:57.704
Yeah.

38:58.204 --> 38:59.439
Great.

39:11.618 --> 39:13.854
Nick, what is all this?

39:14.788 --> 39:15.789
Come here.

39:18.191 --> 39:19.492
Sit down.

39:27.868 --> 39:29.402
(MUSIC PLAYING)

39:29.435 --> 39:30.737
Lindsay...

39:31.605 --> 39:34.107
This song says
all the things

39:34.140 --> 39:36.376
that I haven't
been able to say to you.

39:37.143 --> 39:39.079
It's a little corny.

39:39.112 --> 39:40.547
But I mean it.

39:42.248 --> 39:44.484
♪♪ Lady
Lady...

39:44.518 --> 39:47.253
♪♪ When you're with me
When you're with me,

39:47.287 --> 39:49.355
♪♪ I'm smiling
I'm smiling.

39:49.389 --> 39:51.291
♪♪ Give me
Give me...

39:51.324 --> 39:55.729
(NICK AND RECORD)
<i>♪♪ All your love</i>

39:57.097 --> 39:58.899
<i>♪♪ Your hands</i>

39:58.932 --> 40:03.403
<i>♪♪ Build me up</i>
<i>when I'm sinking</i>

40:04.237 --> 40:06.406
<i>♪♪ Touch me</i>

40:06.439 --> 40:07.841
<i>♪♪ And my troubles</i>

40:07.874 --> 40:10.677
<i>♪♪ All fade</i>
<i>♪♪ All fade</i>

40:11.477 --> 40:12.979
<i>♪♪ Lady...</i>

40:13.013 --> 40:13.847
You see, Lindsay,

40:13.880 --> 40:15.081
<i>♪♪ From the moment</i>
<i>I met you...</i>

40:15.115 --> 40:18.852
Nothing about you and me
should ever be rushed.

40:18.885 --> 40:20.020
<i>♪♪ Standing...</i>

40:20.053 --> 40:21.722
I made that mistake before.

40:22.923 --> 40:24.925
But I'm not gonna
make it with you.

40:26.627 --> 40:28.762
Because we've got time.

40:28.795 --> 40:31.064
We got all the time
in the world.

40:33.333 --> 40:35.435
And you know why?

40:35.468 --> 40:38.939
<i>♪♪ Like a child</i>
<i>who had grown</i>

40:38.972 --> 40:42.809
(RECORD AND NICK)
<i>♪♪ 'Cause you're my lady</i>

40:42.843 --> 40:43.877
<i>♪♪ Yeah</i>

40:43.910 --> 40:46.847
<i>♪♪ Of the morning</i>

40:47.514 --> 40:50.383
<i>♪♪ Love shines</i>

40:50.416 --> 40:53.687
<i>♪♪ In your eyes</i>

40:54.521 --> 40:57.223
<i>♪♪ Sparkling</i>

40:57.257 --> 41:00.561
<i>♪♪ Clear and lovely</i>

41:00.594 --> 41:03.530
♪♪ You're my lady
You're my lady.

41:05.098 --> 41:06.900
<i>♪♪ Lady</i>

41:06.933 --> 41:09.570
<i>♪♪ Turn me on</i>
<i>when I'm lonely...</i>

41:09.603 --> 41:11.037
See, Lindsay,

41:12.472 --> 41:14.074
we were made
for each other.

41:15.642 --> 41:17.744
You want to make out
or something?

41:18.278 --> 41:19.513
No.

41:20.681 --> 41:22.248
All guys
want to make out.

41:24.350 --> 41:25.986
But I just
want to hold you.

41:27.453 --> 41:29.723
<i>♪♪ Sparkling</i>

41:29.756 --> 41:32.859
<i>♪♪ Clear and lovely</i>

41:33.459 --> 41:35.796
<i>♪♪ You're my</i>

41:35.829 --> 41:38.932
♪♪ Lady ♪♪
What's better than this?

41:46.239 --> 41:47.407
Hey.

41:47.440 --> 41:48.642
Hey.

41:50.744 --> 41:52.145
Can I have
the Ding Dong?

41:53.479 --> 41:54.681
Sure.

41:56.382 --> 41:58.051
How was your "date"?

41:58.084 --> 41:59.520
It was OK.

42:00.453 --> 42:02.188
What'd you do?

42:02.222 --> 42:05.592
Mom and Dad
made me watch TV
with them all night.

42:06.059 --> 42:07.694
They were weird.

42:07.728 --> 42:10.030
Yeah, what else is new?

42:10.063 --> 42:12.933
So... So is Nick, like,
your boyfriend now?

42:13.867 --> 42:15.536
I guess so.

42:15.569 --> 42:17.704
But... But he likes you
a lot, right?

42:18.038 --> 42:19.072
Oh, yeah.

42:21.274 --> 42:22.909
I... I wish
Cindy liked me.

42:23.977 --> 42:25.111
She likes you.

42:25.846 --> 42:27.013
Yeah...

42:27.047 --> 42:28.181
Like a friend.

42:29.482 --> 42:32.052
Ooh. That's the worst.

42:33.253 --> 42:35.088
I don't need
another friend.

42:35.121 --> 42:36.690
I already have 2.

42:36.723 --> 42:39.292
I mean, how many
more friends
does a guy need?

42:39.325 --> 42:40.994
(BOTH LAUGH)

42:41.027 --> 42:42.228
(TELEPHONE RINGS)

42:45.832 --> 42:46.833
(RING)

42:50.136 --> 42:51.171
Hello?

42:53.073 --> 42:54.340
Oh, hi, Cindy.

42:55.942 --> 42:57.010
Todd called?

43:06.152 --> 43:07.788
Yeah, it's great.

43:12.626 --> 43:13.827
He said that?

43:22.468 --> 43:25.138
Oh... No!

43:27.307 --> 43:29.075
No, no,
no, I'm not busy.

43:30.911 --> 43:32.779
Tell me
what else happened.
